2. The Spark: Mitochondrial ROS (Reactive Oxygen Species)
Every time your mitochondria turn food into energy, ~1â€“2 % of the electrons â€œleakâ€ onto oxygen, creating superoxide.

That superoxide reacts instantly with NO, turning it into peroxynitrite (ONOOâ»)â€”a damaging oxidant that doesnâ€™t help blood flow at all.
Without antioxidants, you lose a significant chunk of your NO before it even has a chance to act.

your lungs are actually one of the biggest sources of reactiveâ€oxygen species (ROS) in your entire body, and if those radicals overwhelm your defenses you can literally injure the very tissue you need for gas exchange

Metabolic â€œleakâ€ in the alveolarâ€cell mitochondriaâ€”every breath you take requires ATP, and a small fraction of electrons leak off the respiratory chain onto Oâ‚‚, forming superoxide (Oâ‚‚â»Â·).

Pollutants & smoke deliver radical species directly (ozone, nitrogen oxides, particulate matter), or they trigger your immune cells to unleash more ROS to â€œclean upâ€ the insult.





your body is constantly producing small amounts of free radicals simply by breathing, moving, and even thinking, and every environmental insult (pollution, UV, smoke, stress) adds its own burst. Under normal circumstances, your built-in antioxidant systems (enzymes like SOD, catalase, glutathione) plus the antioxidants you consume keep those radicals in check.

But if your radical load outpaces your defensesâ€”because of poor diet, lack of sleep, chronic inflammation, or just not enough dietary antioxidantsâ€”you end up with a persistent â€œoxidative backlog.â€ That shows up as:

