1. The Inflammation â†” ROS Vicious Cycle
Inflammation sparks ROS

Activated immune cells (e.g. neutrophils, macrophages) deliberately generate superoxide, hydrogen peroxide, etc., to kill pathogens or clear debris.

Those ROS also damage your own tissues, which prolongs and amplifies the inflammatory response.

ROS perpetuate inflammation

Free radicals activate transcription factors like NF-ÎºB, which turn on genes for pro-inflammatory cytokines (TNF-Î±, IL-6).

More cytokines recruit more immune cells â†’ more ROS â†’ more inflammation.

If the rate of lung-generated ROS outpaces your local antioxidant defenses, youâ€™ll literally injure your alveoli and airwaysâ€”leading to edema, inflammation, bronchoconstriction, and fibrosis. Thatâ€™s why targeted antioxidant support (both systemic and, if needed, inhaled) is crucial not just for your blood vessels, but to keep your lungs clear so you can keep breathing easily.




